.com/unebobgrenville.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://us.f1.yahoofs.com/users/47663d78/bc/TRIGA/TRIGA.jpg?bcFA2x9AYEIhn4w2" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/6/02 7:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Improving 10-M ORION</span><hr size=1>    I probably have not studied NPR's as long as many of you here so I thought you may be able to help me out here.<br>
   The only way I see a NPR flying anytime soon is as an orbital start-up stage, atmospheric start-up has too many political problems with it. The 10-m design used in the GA study for NASA is enticing as it's small size and weight allow it to be launched and assembled with existing HLVs (like the Energia). It also is comparible in size to NASA's mars propulsion modules. Plus, the larger 20-m versions are simply too massive at full load for reasonable orbital build-up.<br>
   The problem with the 10-m is that it is very inefficient, but this was something GA thought they could improve upon the pulse unit design to produce improved Isp. GA stated in the report that if you could improve the directional force of the pulse unit so that 50% of its mass went towards the pusher, the effective Isp is doubled without significantly increasing ablation. An Isp of 4-5000s would allow it to go to Jupiter. I am not sure if this is achievable, it would take someone with bomb experience to know if this has been accomplished.<br>
   More mass hitting the pusher would probably increase thrust, creating more benefits and problems, requiring heavier shock absorbers. More thrust would be nice, the origonal 3.5E^6N is preaty low.<br>
   I was wondering if any of you had any more ideas on improving performance for my 10-m model? <p>"If," he wispered, "if we could only pick that lock...." - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 975<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/6/02 9:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Improving 10-M ORION</span><hr size=1> It is quite straightforward to create a shaped plasma mass shaped like extended football which would subtend an angle less than 1/2 radian.<br>
<br>
The radiation case around the primary is formed to the shape of a venturi nozzle. At the exit of the nozzle a disk of high-Z (tungsten, typically) material is placed. The channel contains plasma forming filler. This filler is x-ray (and neutron) superheated. The expansion smacks the disk and the resulting shockwave creates a directed column of tungsten plasma.<br>
<br>
This is the basis of old ABM designs.<br>
<br>
yale <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/unebobgrenville.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://us.f1.yahoofs.com/users/47663d78/bc/TRIGA/TRIGA.jpg?bcFA2x9AYEIhn4w2" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/6/02 11:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Improving 10-m ORION</span><hr size=1> The question was not whether it was possible to build a directional warhead, it clearly is, some penitration warheads were also developed with limited directional control. In this case the channel filler is berllium-oxide and tugsten is the propellent. The radiation case, however does not contain all the energy released by the bomb, the channel filler just hopefully absorbs more then the case. By the mid 1960's directional warhead technology had not advanced to the point I was looking for, despite considerable work by Taylor and others. They were not even sure if expelling fully half the mass in one direction would be even possible. I am fairly sure it may be possible now. <p>"If," he wispered, "if we could only pick that lock...." - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/unebobgrenville.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://us.f1.yahoofs.com/users/47663d78/bc/TRIGA/TRIGA.jpg?bcFA2x9AYEIhn4w2" BORDER=0> at: 10/6/02 11:03:39 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 980<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 7:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Improving 10-m ORION</span><hr size=1> Assuming 25 kilograms (rather high) for the &quot;physics package&quot; and 100 kgs of propellent located to one side, then inevitably more then 50% of the mass is directional.<br>
<br>
The better question is whether 50% of the -ENERGY- can be made directional. With a well designed radiation case/reflector chanelling the x-ray flux, I do not see why not.<br>
<br>
yale<br>
 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A> at: 10/7/02 7:28:53 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uzaphod4468.showPublicProfile?language=EN>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 1166<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 8:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.bbc.co.uk/cult/hitchhikers/gallery/images/100/zaphod2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Improving 10-m ORION</span><hr size=1> I would rather just go for the 20 meter design.  Use a Shuttle C variant, Energia or develop the Sea Dragon to use as a HLV to place the components in LEO... assemble and test in orbit.  The added NPR size will provide some measure of safety as the tests can be performed with low yield pulse units first to verify that the 'drive unit' performs as anticipated by the computer sims. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/unebobgrenville.showPublicProfile?language=EN>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://us.f1.yahoofs.com/users/47663d78/bc/TRIGA/TRIGA.jpg?bcFA2x9AYEIhn4w2" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 9:56 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Improving 10-m ORION</span><hr size=1> The problem with the 20-m is that the dry weight of the propulsion unit alone, with no &quot;fuel&quot; or structure is something like 360000kg. While a Sea Dragon could do this, a HLV this size is unlikly to be built anytime in the near future, unfortunately. The 10-m's dry weight is only 91000kg, so could be done with planned or existing HLVs in the near future. Improving the efficiency of the smaller unit keeps expensive launches down. And it is a better reference to other propulsion systems which usually are scaled up to a 10-m vehicle size(to be used with a Mars mission), but no further. The pulse units yields (a nominal 1kt in the GA-5009 study) could be easily reduced for tests.<br>
<br>
Remember the picture of the 20-m you have in the Preserve would take over 13 Sea Dragon-class HLVs to put it in orbit as loaded.<br>
<br>
And the pulse units were conservatively planned to use 2kg of plutonium each, 1kg should work, meaning a vehicle making a 64km/s total mission velocity trip, would only need 1200kg of Pu for fuel. The physics package destroyed the case preventing all the mass and energy to be directed. As I said, Ted Taylor didn't know if it was possible to have that much direction, and he did lots of work on rad case directional bombs, but he did think it could be done in the future(i.e now). An improved case would definitely be needed. <p>"If," he wispered, "if we could only pick that lock...." - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 986<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(10/7/02 10:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=137.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/12.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Improving 10-m ORION</span><hr size=1> 1.2 tonnes of Pu239 is an ENORMOUS amount!<br>
-----<br>
<br>
Yes, the explosion destroys the case, but the X-rays move at &quot;c&quot;, incredibly faster than the rest of the explosion. The radiation channel should be intact for the duration of the energy transfer. <br>
